docs.text: in intolerance , d . w . griffith told four different historical stories at the same time , cutting from one to the other .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: each of the stories builds to a fast-paced climax .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in magnolia , paul thomas anderson tells several stories each just tangentially connected to the others .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: yet the stories and where they are going are all independent .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: what is strange about these stories is that they are all synchronized .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: each story builds to a tense moment ( or what appears to be intended to be a tense moment ) but then lets the tension dissolve .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: while the tension dissipates one character starts singing a song and in each plotline the major characters sing along , even though they are not in the same scene .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: then toward the end the stories each build to a tense moment again .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it is almost as if the characters are somehow psychically linked .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: this creates some strange effects .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the stories are about empty desperate people with dysfunctional relationships .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the strands have varying degrees of bizarre content .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: we have the story of a dying man earl partridge ( jason robards ) wanting to get in touch with his son and make amends .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: phil parma ( philip seymour hoffman ) is his nurse who is frantic to help partridge achieve his final goal .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: partridge's young wife linda ( julianne moore ) is getting more and more anxious as partridge dies , but for an unsuspected reason .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: frank mackey ( tom cruise ) runs the kinds of self-help seminar that businesses like so much , but he aims his at teaching disaffected men how to be real shit-heels in dealing with women in an angry backlash to women's lib .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: officer jim kurring ( john c . reilly ) is a patrolman who has a need to feel he is making the world a better place .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: jimmy gator ( philip baker hall ) hosts a popular children's tv quiz show that really exploits and destroys children as we see from the stories of current quiz kid stanley spector ( jeremy blackman ) and former quiz kid donnie smith ( william h . macy ) .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the film juggles all these stories for over three hours , but even after all this time not one story is resolved satisfactorily .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: each story moves toward a single bizarre common climax , but it is not one that seems to do much but derail each story .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the common climax itself is ambiguous in many ways and it fails to really tie up any of the stories .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the film seems to be built around strange events and weird history , but it really has little to do with the content of the stories , though they all are connected in part by one weird event .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: magnolia will probably bring some much deserved attention to paul thomas anderson , though in my opinion his two previous films , hard eight and boogie nights were better told stories .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it is interesting that one starts to look forward to actors from anderson's company .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: john c . reilly seems to be a standard fixture .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: particularly notable is philip baker hall who gave a mesmerizing performance from the first scene of hard eight .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: here he several of the characters are mesmerizing , but that characteristic is not really used .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: as studies of characters these stories are each worth following .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: as well-rounded stories with a beginning , middle and end , they leave something to be desired .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: but the film is willing to do the unexpected and that helps make the film worth sitting through .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: i rate it a 7 on the 0 to 10 scale and a low +2 on the -4 to +4 scale .

docs.text: during the strange climactic event of the film we get multiple messages from the filmmaker that the event we are seeing really does happen .

docs.text: and in actual fact , it does .

docs.text: since biblical times rains of frogs have been interpreted as signs of displeasure of the gods .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it is , however , a perfectly natural , if somewhat unnerving , phenomenon .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the cause is associated with whirlwinds .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: we know that tornadoes over land can rip up land and even objects of some size from the ground and hurl them into the air , holding them aloft .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the reader may remember the unfortunate cow in twister .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: smaller objects can be hurled high into the atmosphere and then be kept aloft by the updrafts for surprisingly long periods of time much as hail and chunks of ice are .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: when the whirlwind is over water , animals near the surface , frequently fish and frogs , may suffer the same fate .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: essentially they are vacuumed up by the whirlwind , held aloft by updrafts , and finally dropped elsewhere .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: so while the rain is possible , some doubts do creep in .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the rain of frogs depicted in this film may be of greater scale than i had pictured for a rain of frogs .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it seems unlikely the frogs would still be alive when dropped .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: it is not clear that geographic conditions are right for los angeles to have this sort of phenomenon .

docs.text: ( frankly i have no idea on these points . )
